1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 Okay. Good. So, hello. Well, from your side, it seems the connection is good. From my side, don't be surprised if I'm disconnected, because I'm speaking from Ukraine. We have blackouts, we have electricity like two or three hours per day, and at the moment we don't have electricity. So I'm at home and we have like a generator and batteries, and that's the only way we can be connected.

2
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 But I hope it will go smoothly. So, I'm going to be talking about the myth of 1054. I will give you a historical overview to demonstrate how kind of symbolic is this date, not really. Its weight nowadays

3
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
 is much, much stronger than it used to be in the 11th century.

4
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 Let me begin with a very general statement that the church, Christian church, was always one, but Christians were never completely united. Since the apostolic era,

5
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 there have been divisions in the global Christian community which are called schisms, from the Greek word schizma. Schizma. I think it is incorrect to speak about church divisions, because

6
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 the church is always one and cannot be divided. Therefore, to speak about church divisions is like an oxymoron. It doesn't make sense.

7
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 It is theologically more correct to speak about divisions among Christians. Such divisions have existed since the apostolic era.

8
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:55,000
 They have been always perceived as tragedies. The great Syrian theologian Ephraim of Syria expressed this feeling of tragedies in one of his songs from Carmina Nisibana.

9
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 I quote him. And for me in my misery intercede, O church. I have grieved for thy divisions. May I rejoice in thy union. And with thee and under thy protection may I enter the kingdom.

10
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 It is easy for Ephraim to provoke, from the Ephraim to provoke a division, but very difficult to heal one.

11
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 Nevertheless, God has the power to bring the church back to unity. And again I quote Ephraim, the Syrian "Lord, for a surgeon it is simple to cut off a limb, but it is not easy for him to fasten it back in its place.

12
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
 But for thee, Lord, both are easy, for thou art God."

13
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 End of quote. Ephraim was right. It may take months to provoke a schism and centuries to heal one.

14
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:55,000
 The longest schism in the Christian history happened in the East in the 5th century.

15
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 This schism, which I call Great Schism I, had the largest scale the Christian world had ever known.

16
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 As a result of this schism, three Eastern Commonwealths emerged: the Byzantine, the Oriental, and the Church of the East.

17
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 This schism triggered a series of events, eventually leading to the second Great Schism,

18
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 the division between the Eastern and Western churches.

19
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:25,000
 It is commonly believed that this schism happened in 1054.

20
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 However, the process of division had begun much earlier, several centuries before that date, and were not completed in the 11th century.

21
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:49,000
 Some scholars believe that only the trauma of the Fourth Crusade and the sack of Constantinople by the Latins in 1204 made the Easternists mentally break up with the West.

22
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:54,000
 This is particularly the point of George Democopoulos in his studies.

23
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 One can even suggest that this schism was accomplished as late as the 18th century.

24
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 In 1729, the congregation Propaganda Fide formally prohibited participation in sacraments over confessional borders.

25
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 So essentially they prohibited the Catholics to give communion to the Orthodox.

26
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 Reciproqually, in 1755, the Ecumenical Patriarchate issued a similar prohibition.

27
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:30,000
 So the Ecumenical Patriarchate prohibited as faithful, the Orthodox to take communion from the Catholics.

28
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 So that, I think, could be seen as a formal kind of sacramental finale of this centuries-long process of having the evolution of the schism, the great schism II.

29
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 The early cessation of communion between Rome and Constantinople, which lasted several years, happened in the 5th century and has been called the Akashian schism.

30
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:10,000
 It took place from 484 through 519 and was caused by the policies of Emperor Zeno to undermine the Council of Chalcedon.

31
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 The Emperor was supported by the patriarch of Constantinople, Akashius, who was in office from 472 through 489.

32
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 However, Pope Felix, who was in office from 483 through 492, considered this move a betrayal of Orthodoxy and excommunicated the patriarch of Constantinople.

33
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:41,000
 The cessation of communion between the churches of Rome and Constantinople that followed can be formally defined as a schism.

34
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 It became an aftershock of the great schism I between the Byzantine and Oriental churches.

35
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:53,000
 It also created a dangerous precedent for the events that would happen a few centuries later.

36
00:05:53,000 --> 00:06:00,000
 Fortunately, the Akashian schism did not mutate into a larger division.

37
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 It was eventually settled through the intervention of the imperial authority.

38
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 The same authority, however, created political preconditions for further alienation between the Eastern and Western churches.

39
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:16,000
 Excuse me.

40
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 An apple of discord for the two parts of Christendom became the region sandwiched between Asia Minor and Italy, Eastern Illyria.

41
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 Actually, it included Croatia as well.

42
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 After Emperor Theodosius divided the Roman Empire into Eastern and Western parts, Eastern Illyria became administratively subordinated to Rome.

43
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:48,000
 Ecclesially, however, the Church of Constantinople continued claiming its rights over it.

44
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 The Church of Rome contested these claims.

45
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 Both the political and ecclesial statuses of this territory were rearranged by a latter imperial decrees.

46
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 So that Church of Rome was right to accuse Constantinople of political interventions.

47
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:16,000
 When Christianity was adopted by the Bulgars, who had settled in Illyria in the 6th-7th centuries, the Churches of Rome and Constantinople contested control over the Bulgarian Church.

48
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 All Christian divisions were caused by the combination of theological, social, and political factors in different proportions.

49
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:33,000
 It is difficult to say in what proportions politics and theology contributed to the Great Schism too.

50
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:42,000
 The issue of Eastern Illyria was one of the political factors, while the controversy about Filioque was one of the theological factors of the Schism.

51
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:48,000
 I will not analyze the theological side of Filioque, but will stay on its political side.

52
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 It had to do with the imperial ideology of the time.

53
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 Let me make a footnote.

54
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 Let me say a few words or other sentences about the political aspect of Filioque.

55
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 The universal political canon of the time was that there could be only one empire.

56
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 And that empire was Roman.

57
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 The Byzantines believed that their emperor was the true and only Roman emperor, the ruler of the world.

58
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 The Franks, a new power consolidating Western Europe, initially accepted such a role of the Byzantine basilepsis.

59
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 However, at some moment they demonstrated an ambition to appropriate the imperial status for themselves.

60
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 Charlemagne made a decisive step in this direction when he was crowned by Pope Leo III on Christmas 800 as Imperator Romanorum.

61
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 Coronation by the Pope, however, was only a part of the legitimization of the Frankish ruler as emperor.

62
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 According to the aforementioned political philosophy of the time, there could be only one Roman emperor in the world.

63
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 Therefore, to complete his own legitimization as an emperor, Charlemagne had to delegitimize the Byzantine emperors.

64
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 So this process of emergence of a new emperor had two sides, kind of boosting my own legitimization and delegitimizing my opponent, another contester, another pretender for this position.

65
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:37,000
 In other words, to become a legit emperor, Charlemagne had to prove that the empires of Constantinople had lost their legitimacy.

66
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 His court, ideologists and theologians, who actually were the same people usually, such as our queen of York, elaborated arguments to prove Charlemagne's claim.

67
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 First, they used the situation that the Byzantine throne at the time was held by a woman, Empress Irini.

68
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
 They argued that only a man could be a proper emperor.

69
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:09,000
 In addition to this sexist argument, second, they utilized Tiloque.

70
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 That train of thought was the following: since at least Theodosius I, the orthodoxy of faith had been one of the main factors of legitimacy for an emperor that distinguished him from the usurpers.

71
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 If the Frankish theologians could prove that Tiloque was the only orthodox interpretation of the trinity, they would claim that the easterners, who did not hold it, were apostates and usurpers.

72
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 Only the Frankish kings, who upheld the orthodox doctrine of Tiloque, would claim to be true Roman emperors.

73
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 Under the pressure of this political ideology, Tiloque, from an optional theologoumenon, so to say, an optional theological idea, turned to a mandatory doctrine with far-reaching political ramifications.

74
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 In the words of Edward Sychensky, I quote him, from the obscure theological backwaters that bothered only scholars, the issue of Tiloque quickly catapulted to become a casus belli.

75
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 End of quote.

76
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:23,000
 The trophy in this quasi-theological bellum that the Frankish kings had waged was the crown of the Roman Empire.

77
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 The easterners picked up the fight.

78
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 They utilized the issue of Tiloque for their own political purposes.

79
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:45,000
 Just as Tiloque tried through Tiloque to undermine the imperial legitimacy of the eastern Roman or Byzantine rulers, the latter did the same in the opposite direction.

80
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 By insisting that Tiloque is a heretical doctrine, the Byzantines presented Shalman as a typical usurper of the imperial status.

81
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 These theological underpinnings propelled Tiloque to a prime theological issue that occupied the best Greco-Roman minds.

82
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 Eventually, Tiloque became perceived as a symbol of differences, either imagined or real, between the east and west.

83
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 The patriarch of Constantinople 40 years was a protagonist of the Byzantine deconstruction of the Frankish theopolitical constructions based on Tiloque.

84
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 He was both a statesman and a churchman.

85
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 He clearly saw how politics and theology had been mixed in the Frankish take on Tiloque.

86
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 He also knew how to deconstruct the Franks and turn their arguments against themselves.

87
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 Although Fortius, in the intra-Byzantine policies and quarrels, defended some significant autonomy of the church from the state, when it came to the external threats, like from the Franks, he was an adamant patriot of his state.

88
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:04,000
 And he advocated for the interests of the state, not just of the church.

89
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 Thank you very much.

90
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:10,000
 Frankish attacks and Byzantine counter-attacks led to a schism, which was called Fortium.

91
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 Very well described, as you know, by Francis Dvornik.

92
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 It was a cessation in communion between Rome and Constantinople, which had multiple pretexts, including disagreements on ritual practices.

93
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:28,000
 The Fortean schism was shorter than the preceding Akashian schism.

94
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 It lasted from 863 through 867, four years only.

95
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 However, during the Fortean schism, most arguments were elaborated upon, which later would be utilized for a much longer schism.

96
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 The Akashian and Fortean schism set unfortunate precedence for the great schism between the East and Western churches that lasts to our days.

97
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 Before the Fortean schism, a rich diversity of beliefs and practices was tolerated in the East and the West.

98
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:09,000
 The schisms reduced the space of pluralism and tolerance.

99
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:22,000
 Each side now insisted that only its practices and beliefs were right, and the other was wrong, even though they did not bother themselves with such differences earlier.

100
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:29,000
 In this polemical spirit, Forteus drafted a catalogue of the assumed Western mistakes.

101
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:34,000
 He disseminated it among his peers, the Patriarchs.

102
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:46,000
 In his encyclical letter to the Eastern Patriarchs sent in 866, Forteus informed them about the activities of the Western missionaries in Bulgaria.

103
00:14:46,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 Amongst the unacceptable Latin practices and beliefs, Forteus listed fasting on Saturdays, celibacy of priests, prismation by bishops, and finally the Filioque.

104
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 Surprisingly, this list misses an issue that was really divisive.

105
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:15,000
 Moreover, it underpinned most other divisive issues between the East and the West.

106
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:17,000
 This was the issue of primacy.

107
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:29,000
 The Western theologians interpreted the primacy of Roman bishops as a divine institution established by the divine right.

108
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 They called it "us divinum", the divine right.

109
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:34,000
 The East disagreed with such an interpretation.

110
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:40,000
 It ascribed such divine right to all Patriarchs or known of them.

111
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 So, either all the Patriarchs have this right or none of them.

112
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,000
 No exception to Rome.

113
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:59,000
 In the latter case, the case that the Patriarchs are perceived as non-having "us divinum", underpinning their authority,

114
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 of the "us divinum".

115
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:05,000
 The Eastern theologians interpreted primacy as conventional.

116
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 It stems not from God, but from the consent of other churches and imperial authorities.

117
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:23,000
 The East also disagreed with the Western interpretation of primacy as based on the identification of the Roman sea with the universal church.

118
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 The Western discovery of Aristotle and his categories apparently facilitated such an identification.

119
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:40,000
 The basic distinction with which the Aristotelian logics enriched Christian theology was the one between commonality and particularity.

120
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:48,000
 Medieval Western ecclesiologists effectively identified the Roman sea with the common nature of the church.

121
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:58,000
 While they regarded other local churches as particularities of this nature.

122
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 They also adopted the Neoplatonic outlook on the category of commonality as more important than the category of particularities.

123
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 Such an outlook corroborated the growing Western consensus that the Roman church was more important than other local churches, including the Patriarchate of Constantinople.

124
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:22,000
 Such ideas can be traced in several documents and practices of the time.

125
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:27,000
 One of them is Donation of Constantine, a forgery produced in the 8th century.

126
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:35,000
 It tells a legend that Pope Sylvester cured Emperor Constantine of leprosy and baptized him.

127
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:40,000
 In return, Constantine granted the Pope primacy over the universal church.

128
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:48,000
 The idea of the Roman universal jurisdiction was implemented in the Western church policies during the Fourth Crusade.

129
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 After the Latins occupied Constantinople, the Pope appointed a new patriarch of the patriarchal city of the capital city under his jurisdiction.

130
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:05,000
 This move corresponded to the Western perception of the Roman church as embodying the universal church.

131
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 After the Byzantines restored their control over Constantinople, the Roman popes continued treating the patriarchs of Constantinople as their own subjects.

132
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:31,000
 In medieval Roman ecclesiology, the idea of Rome as the quintessence of the universal church became linked with the idea of particular salvation.

133
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:49,000
 In particular salvation appropriated by everyone through the synergy with the divine grace and thus appropriating salvation for him or herself.

134
00:18:49,000 --> 00:19:02,000
 This bull, papal bull, papal bull Unam Sanctum, the famous one, which was promulgated in 1302 by Pope Boniface VIII, stated:

135
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:12,000
 "We declare, we proclaim, we define that it is absolutely necessary for salvation that every human creature be subject to the Roman pontiff."

136
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 This bull also implied that to be true church, any local church has to subject itself to the Sea of Rome, just as every Christian to be saved has to recognize the authority of the Pope.

137
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:31,000
 Both ideas did not make sense to the Easterners.

138
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:37,000
 On the one hand, they also believed that particular salvation is possible only in the universal church.

139
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:48,000
 On the other hand, since the church of Rome was for them a particular church, to confine salvation to only one particular church would be dangerous for salvation.

140
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:53,000
 Roman claims reduced the availability of salvation.

141
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 It was if someone would say that one can be saved only in the church of Alexandria and not in the church of Antioch, for example.

142
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 The Easterners, thus, objected to the Western claims for universal jurisdiction on the satiriological grounds.

143
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:17,000
 This framework may help us better understand the story of Anathemas in 1054.

144
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:28,000
 At the turn of the second Christian millennium, neither the East nor the West could tolerate any more their growing differences in interpreting primacy and jurisdictions.

145
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:40,000
 In 1009, the patriarchs Sergius II of Constantinople and Pope Sergius IV of Rome stopped commemorating each other.

146
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
 It was called the Schism of two Sergii.

147
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 It was a prelude to more dramatic events some 50 years later.

148
00:20:48,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 A chain of events was triggered when Pope Leo IX sent to Constantinople Cardinal Humbert of Silvia Candida with a mission to secure Byzantine help against the Normans ravaging papal dominions in Italy.

149
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:10,000
 Although not a remarkable theologian, Humbert was a zealot of the new Roman ecclesiology.

150
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:26,000
 On the margins of political negotiations at the Byzantine court, the papal legates discussed some theological issues, including the Western practice of using unleavened bread in the Eucharist.

151
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:33,000
 At that time, this issue seemed to be the most discussed in the theological exchanges between the East and the West.

152
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:39,000
 Such exchanges were routine rituals performed during political missions like this one.

153
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:42,000
 Theological discussions did not go well.

154
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:53,000
 They were exacerbated by bad personal chemistry between Humbert and Patriarch Michael I Keralarius.

155
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:00,000
 The Patriarch demonstratively mistreated the papal delegation.

156
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:05,000
 The unnerved cardinal did not grant it to Keralarius.

157
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:21,000
 On July 16, 1054, he rushed to the Cathedral of San Sophia before the patriarchal liturgy started and placed on the holy table the bull of excommunication of Michael and some other hierarchs close to the Patriarch.

158
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:26,000
 After that, the Roman delegation promptly left the city.

159
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 They were fearing their retaliation, justifiably so.

160
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 However, Humbert could not anathematize a pat-check in the Pope's name because Pope Leo IX, who had sent him, was already dead.

161
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:45,000
 Humbert acted in a field of hysterics.

162
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:53,000
 He also wanted to demonstrate that he meant it when he insisted on the Roman prerogatives early in the discussions.

163
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 Now, he was applying these prerogatives in practice.

164
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:01,000
 The same hysterical was the Constantinopolitan reaction.

165
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:16,000
 Michael, Patriarch Michael, Keralarius, immediately convened an endimus synodos, the so-called ad hoc synod council, which condemned those who had dared to anathematize the Patriarch.

166
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:20,000
 The emperor enhanced this decision with an addict.

167
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:31,000
 The primate of the Constantinopolitan church was as politically ambitious as his Western counterparts.

168
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:36,000
 He notoriously wore purple shoes, the imperial color.

169
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 That is why he presented the assault against him as an attack on the imperial authority.

170
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:49,000
 He also identified the patriarchal office with the Church as such, a common perception even today.

171
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:58,000
 In his eyes, as well as in the eyes of later generations, anathema against the Patriarch meant anathema against the Church.

172
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:08,000
 A minor episode caused by the emotional incontinence of two ambitious hierarchs thus came down to history as a great schism.

173
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:20,000
 It was not so much this episode per se as the medieval tendency to equate hierarchy with the Church that made the great schism great and possible.

174
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:32,000
 Therefore, I believe the ecclesiological underpinnings, the idea that the Church is equal to the hierarchy, is the framework that facilitated the schism to happen.

175
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:44,000
 And I believe the schism can be undone if we get rid of this medieval identification of the Church with the hierarchy of the Patriarch that had caused the schism in the first place.

176
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:53,000
 In the meantime, Michael Kirillarius informed other Eastern Patriarchs about what happened in the capital.

177
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:57,000
 Not all of them shared Michael's uncontrolled anxiety.

178
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 "Patrick, Peter III of Antioch, for example, tried to count down Michael and reminded him that the Latins are still our brothers," I quote Peter, "even if from rusticity or ignorance they attain the same level of accuracy that we ask of our own people."

179
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:31,000
 Another prominent hierarchy of the Archbishop Theophilus Theophilus Theophilus also believed that the difference between the East and the West should not become a reason for breakups.

180
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 He blamed the Eastern zealots who, I quote him, "through unmeasured zeal and lack of humility were quick to bring all sorts of accusations against the West without thinking through them thoroughly."

181
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:52,000
 The anathemas of 1054 passed almost unnoticed by the contemporaries.

182
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:57,000
 However, they grew enormous in the perception of future generations.

183
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:03,000
 Now we see them as a breaking point in their relations between the East and the West.

184
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:11,000
 Because of the tremendous symbolic significance of these anathemas in modern perception, there was an attempt to undo them.

185
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:32,000
 In December 1965, soon after the historic meeting of Patriarch Athenagoras of Constantinople with Pope Paul VI in Jerusalem in January 1964, the two seas promulgated a joint declaration.

186
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 It was read synchronically in St. Peter's Cathedral in Rome and the Patriarchal Cathedral of St. George in Istanbul.

187
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:43,000
 This declaration was a symbolic gesture.

188
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:52,000
 It did not mean to or intend to mean the restoration of communion between the two churches.

189
00:26:52,000 --> 00:27:02,000
 It acknowledged that what happened in 1054 was a mutual excommunication not of the churches but only of some individuals.

190
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:20,000
 The lifting of anathemas was appreciated by many in both churches as a token of the restoration of trust between them, not of the relations yet between them, but at least of trust, which is the first step towards the restoration of communion.

191
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:27,000
 Some conservatives, however, perceived this event as an act of apostasy.

192
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 They ascribed to it more significance than what was intended with this act.

193
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:44,000
 Actually, both sides acted as if the anathemas of 1054 were a sort of myth.

194
00:27:44,000 --> 00:28:03,000
 So the radical anti-ecumenical reaction to the lifting of anathemas among the conservatives is a consequence of this mythologization of the year 1054.

195
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:22,000
 Therefore, my kind of last conclusion, by demythologization of 1054, we can facilitate the reception of the lifting of anathemas among those who object this lifting.

196
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 So it's important to, I believe, to strip this date of unnecessary significance and mythology.

197
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:33,000
 Thank you for your attention.

198
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:34,000
 Thank you for your attention.

199
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:37,000
 Thank you for your attention.

